Author: @Rekaert
Comment:
One of the things I love about it is how some encounters organically lead into another. Case in point ...

So I happened up on a deal going down, four men haggling about what appeared to be a stolen wagon. It was night, so I slid over and took a good position behind an old stone wall. The men started arguing, guns were drawn, and in no time at all two of them were dead, one being coldly executed once down with a shot to the head.

I figured these were probably not the nicest of men, so decided to take them out. As it happens I had my new Winchester rifle that I stole whilst rescuing a store owner's male sex slave, (whole different story), and I dropped both scumbags pretty quickly.

Then I figured there's me, four dead men, and one wagon that's very likely stolen anyway, so hell, I may as well take the wagon and sell it to a fence at Emerald Ranch. Whilst in that neck of the woods and with more cash than I had before, I remembered that Marston had a plan to take down a train.

For someone who left camp to go hunt a wolf, things really seemed to spiral out of control.

Author: @theycallmerobb
Comment:
It is crazy that so many do not know these and more‚Ä¶like:
The gold bar at Limpany and later Braithwaite Manor respawn if you close the box. This is also true of large jewelry bags and cash in the abandoned church and at the edge of the swamp near Shady Hollow, the chest near the split in the train tracks near the north end of the swamp near Saint Denis. Gold nuggets and cash in the abandoned fort, free respawning tomahawks and throwing knives at 6 point cabin, the two gold bars in the fallen rail cars respawn for you as John in the epilogue, and of course that Hanging Dog and Chez Porter have respawning cash stacks of $110 and a Jewelry bag (Chez) every couple of days. But a ton of things respawn if you close the box or drawers.
You can easily have 10+ gold bars before you ever unlock the fence by revisiting Limpany every time you pass to check. 
Once in the epilogue money is too easy. If you were smart and sold everything and played Aberdeen Pig Farm right before the last Arthur mission, and didn‚Äôt go back for the cash you have about 80-100k after buying everything as Arthur. 
Go get the respawning shotguns at Watson‚Äôs Cabin and Chez and then run into horse riders between the two to get a Litchfield Repeater and Schofield, head to Fort Riggs and take on the Skinner ambush and you can get the bow and arrows to complete anything left over as John, without waiting for Arthur‚Äôs weapons‚Ä¶all the while visiting places like Lobos camps and Rigwood Farm for cash, ammo, weapons and unlimited gold ingots without even opening the box (with only short rides to the train tracks north to force respawn).

Money, weapons and gear are the least of your problems in RDR2 or any Rockstar game for that matter‚Ä¶

Getting Gold Medals in 70 missions and Guarma compendium animals is far harder than money/gear. That stuff is free. You never need to buy a weapon in RDR2 except for those sold at the fence.

Author: @RibeyeRob
Comment:
You should absolutely buy RDR 2 no matter what year it is. I have been playing it for about two years now and am 97% through. I have finished the story but still have stuff to find south of Blackwater.

I was in no rush to complete this game and have had breaks over the last two years. I wanted it to last as long as possible as it will be years before RDR 3 comes out. I have tried to do everything there is to do and find all the collectables which I am proud to say I have nearly achieved without the use of any guides or googling.

I have put around 2000 hours in to the game so far and from the start I have been using the in-game camera to capture glorious images of the world and many action scenes along with all the missions. I have nearly 9,000 images so far and plan to put them in a video when I complete the game with music from the RDR 2 album playing throughout the video. My current guess if I display each image for 4 seconds with a fade in and out means the end video will be around 16 hours long which I will have to split in two videos due to YouTubes upload limit of 12 hours.

I am guessing nobody has made a video like this of RDR 2 so it will be my tribute to what is in my opinion the greatest video game ever made. I hope to finish the game and have the two videos made and uploaded sometime in 2025 so keep an eye on my channel if that's something you'd enjoy watching. ü§†

Author: @RIP_Greedo
Comment: What's great about Red Dead is that, while GTA is a vulgar satire of contemporary American culture that honestly gets a little old, Red Dead (especially 2) has a deep, mature appreciation of its setting. The landscape, the animals are brought to live in a realistic (seeming) way. The soundtrack is an incredible evocation of American folk music forms. There is so much to experience in this game just observing and taking in the environment. While GTA wrings a laugh out an annoying NPC being kicked in the head, Red Dead invites you to listen and watch as moose takes a drink in a stream. Or in reading Arthur's journal and seeing his drawings (and his appreciation) of the things he (you) sees in the world. The frontier spirit is well captured not in Dutch's gang, but in all the civilians they come across. The dramatic irony of the game (which Arthur comes to realize as the plot progresses) is that most of the people the gang encounters (and usually robs) are just trying to make a living in a difficult environment and that the gang, while itself being a sort of family, is an anti-social force in this environment. This is by far the best game I've ever played in my 38 years of life.

Author: @Luna_moon_1127
Comment: Honestly, before anyone judges me for this trust me, read the whole comment I really like horse games as someone who rides horses in real life and I like looking for realistic details in horse games. I am aware that this game is not specifically a horse game but the fact that there are so many realistic elements to the horses, behaviour and animations is amazing to me. I really like that you have to actually care for the horse in order to maintain their health and stamina. I really like how the horses will spook when they come across predators I like how sometimes even when you fire your gun in the game the horse will spook depending on the horse that you have. I have some horses that will completely stop running if I fire a gun and spook a little bit and I have another horse that will just keep running and doesn‚Äôt even care when I fire the gun. so, even though I started originally playing this game as I kinda just played it in a free mode version, and it just rode around and caught wild horses and teamed them, and sold them that kind of thing and I did like a little bit of hunting now I‚Äôm actually getting into playing the story mode of the game but like I said, there are so many realistic details to the horses like the fact that if you leave them in water and get off them, they‚Äôll get out of the water the fact that they will have steam cum off them if you come from a cold area to a hot area or it might be vice versa I‚Äôm not sure the fact that when it rains you can see your horses coat visibly get wet when you ride through muddy areas your horse visibly gets dirty. All of these things are so realistic but there‚Äôs such small details I just really like that they put into it and it even though I‚Äôm not. Just playing the game for the horse mechanics anymore like I was I still very much I do appreciate them and there are times where I just played free mode and I‚Äôll just go and tame a bunch of wild horses and sell them or I‚Äôll just ride around on my horse and do you like trail rides around the area because I do really like the graphics of the game as well. All in all the behaviour for the horses in the second game is just a lot better compared to the first one from what I can see in this one, and I absolutely love the behaviors, the graphics the details that they add to the horses is just perfect.Ôøº

Comment:
RDR2 is an experience.

Living breathing world that changes and is fully interactive. NPCs remember you along with the town with individual and mission actions. Side missions don't just have throw away characters. They have actual memorable personalities.

The biggest thing aside from the amazing world in the subject of textures. We're still discovering things years later.

Also the story is bar none the best because not only the development of the main character but the whole of all characters. Along with the fact there's still plenty to do even after you complete the main story.

Author: @37Kilo2
Comment:
This game is so damn good. I'm currently on my third playthrough. My second play, I got annoyed with the speed of Chapter I, but recently, I didn't really think it was slow. I think it was just right. You get to learn the crew, you receive just enough information about the Blackwater job to grab your interest, you're given time to learn the controls. Guarma, on the other hand, I could never learn to like that part of the game. It felt so out of place. 

I think I still love RDR more than RDR2, but it's extremely close. 2 improved on the first in every way, but 1 absolutely blew me away when it came out. My life was consumed by it. 

If every AAA game was equal in quality to RDR2, I'd happily pay $100 for all of them. Lastly, I genuinely hope to get a third game in the series, but I'm not sure who the story would follow. It wouldn't be the same without the Van Der Linde gang.

Author: @LinweAifhyl
Comment:
The turning point that made me start to love Arthur was reading his journal. Before that, Arthur was for me kind of a mindless brute, always choosing violence over words and being unapologetic for it. The story was interesting but the main character was meh.

But then, after Arthur goes collecting the money people owe you (around the beginning of the game), I randomly explored the camp and found Arthur's journal and started reading it.
The journal retraces the main story point but adds Arthur inner thoughts about what happened. And it changed my entire view of the character because he writes about how he always has violent impulse and he doesn't know why and he wishes he didn't and how affected he is about everything. He talks about his doubts and worries and things you don't really get when you just play him, even on high honor. 
There's also a bunch of sketches he drew from places, animal and plants you discover in the world and I found it endearing to imagine a man I thought was a dumb brute, sitting down to sketch a squirrel.

I know Arthur has a redemption arc and you see more and more of this caring, non-violent side and I would've eventually start to like him but reading his journal changed my entire perspective really early in the game and i'm so glad I read it and continued to read it throughout the story to know his opinion on Dutch's decline.

Arthur Morgan is easily my favorite video game character now.

Author: @angryclown1990
Comment:
There should not, and will not, be a Red Dead Redeption 3. That story is over. There is nowhere else to go with it, there is no way to explore that story or any of its characters further that will not ruin and insult the legacy of those two games. 

However, there WILL be another Red Dead game. Other than GTA it's one of Rockstar's biggest titles. Between RDR1&2 and Red Dead Revolver, Rockstar has helped keep the Western alive in video games. The next Red Dead game has no choice but to go back in time, which is a good thing. The next story needs to be set some time around the Civil War, or during the days of railroad construction, or the wars with the native nations. Maybe explore the conflict between cattle barons and sod busters. Give us a female character to play as. Let us play as a black, native, Hispanic, Chinese or mixed race character. Tell wild west story from their ethnic perspectives. The naming convention even has a lot of meat still on it. 

Red Dead Railroad
Red Dead Revenge
Red Dead Roundup 
Red Dead Reconing
Red Dead Resolve
Red Dead Ruin

The story of Red Dead Redemption is over, there's nothing more that needs to be said there. No, other characters  in that story don't need their own game. We don't need all the questions answered, we don't need more of their history explored. Redemption is done, over. Let it go. 

But Rockstar hasn't even scratched the surface of this incredible western setting they have created. There are literally unlimited stories to tell, and if they want to make lots of money, we will return to the western world of Red Dead in a completely new story.

Author: @Beastiebubs
Comment: I think that people heavily misunderstand the importance of the Guarma chapter. The Guarma chapter proves that the Dutch‚Äôs gang will always be hunted, and that violence will follow them no matter the place. This theme of the gang, but more importantly Arthur, feeling like that they‚Äôre from a bygone era is prominent throughout Red Dead, and in my humble opinion, that makes Guarma is one of the most effective parts of the game when it comes to delivering that message. (It also allegorically shows how Arthur feels in the rapidly evolving and ever changing world of 1899, with his experience drawing clear parallels to him being washed up on and stranded on an island, unaware of the new world he‚Äôs in.)

Author: @t3hpoopsmith
Comment:
Biggest problem with the game was the juxtaposition between the campaign and open world.   Everything is open and sandboxy except the actual game itself.  When you actually want to make progress in the game you are given no agency or choice and how to go about it.  You have to do exactly what the screen says or you fail the mission.   What's the point in designing all these crazy physics and open world mechanics if they cannot be used in the actual campaign?   

A lot of the controls were also clunky and the details that were initially impressive became kind of a slog that would slow the game down.  

The story was decent. But at the end of the day Even the best video game stories are not as good as movies or books and I play for gameplay.
